  1. (5 pts) You should be able to see an increasing relationship between height and mass. Fit a linear model to the data and save the model object as “HtWtModel”. Extract the slope and intercept parameters from the model.
HtWtModel <- lm(mass ~ height, filtered_data)

slope <- coef(HtWtModel)[2]  
intercept <- coef(HtWtModel)[1]  

cat("Slope:", slope, "\n")
## Slope: 0.6213599
cat("Intercept:", intercept, "\n")
## Intercept: -32.54076
  1. (10 pts) Add the model fitted values to the StarWars data frame along with the regression model confidence intervals. Create a scatterplot With the fitted line and confidence band displayed.
StarWars$FittedValues <- predict( HtWtModel, newdata = StarWars ) 
StarWars$CI_Lower <- predict( HtWtModel, newdata = StarWars, interval = "confidence" )[, "lwr"]
StarWars$CI_Upper <- predict( HtWtModel, newdata = StarWars, interval = "confidence" )[, "upr"]

ggplot( StarWars, aes( x = height, y = mass ) ) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line( aes( y = FittedValues ), color = "red" ) +
  geom_ribbon( aes( ymin = CI_Lower, ymax = CI_Upper ), fill = "red", alpha = 0.2 ) +
  labs(title = "Height vs. Mass in StarWars Characters",
       x = "Height",
       y = "Mass")

  1. (10 pts) Download and create a dataframe from the file UKGDP.csv. This data contains Monthly GDP figures for the United Kingdom (Billions of pounds). Create a dataframe from this data that contains three columns: Year, Month, and GDP. Create a graph that shows the monthly GDP over time.
UKGDP <- read.csv("~/Downloads/UKGDP.csv")

month_order <- c("January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", 
                 "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December")

UKGDP_long <- gather(UKGDP, key = "Month", value = "GDP", -Year) %>%
  mutate(Month = factor(Month, levels = month_order))

ggplot(UKGDP_long, aes(x = Month, y = GDP, group = Year, color = Year )  ) +
  geom_line()

  1. (15 pts) The function rnorm() simulates the selection of a random sample from a normal population. For example, rnorm(40,20,3) will produce a vector of 40 values randomly drawn from a population that is normally distributed with mean 20 and standard deviation 3. Write some code to find out how likely it is that a sample mean is larger than 21 if it is calculated from a random sample of size 40 drawn from a normally distributed population with mean 20 and standard deviation 3? Hint: Use a loop to create a thousand random samples and for each test to see if the sample mean turns out greater than 21. What proportion were greater than 21?
sims <- 1000
over_21 <- 0

for (i in 1:sims) 
  {
  random_sample <- rnorm(40, 20, 3)
  sample_mean <- mean(random_sample)

  if (sample_mean > 21) 
    {
     over_21 = over_21 + 1
    }
  }

cat("Proportion of sample means greater than 21:", over_21 / sims, "\n")
## Proportion of sample means greater than 21: 0.013
  1. (10 pts) Use your code from 13 to create a function that allows the user to input the sample size, mean, standard deviation and comparison value and outputs the estimated probability.
est_prob <- function(p_size, p_mean, p_sd, threshhold)
{
  over_thresh <- 0
  sims <- 1000
  
  for (i in 1:sims) 
  {
  random_sample <- rnorm(p_size, p_mean, p_sd)
  sample_mean <- mean(random_sample)

  if (sample_mean > threshhold) 
    {
     over_thresh = over_thresh + 1
    }
  }
  cat("Proportion of sample means greater than 21:", over_thresh / sims, "\n")
}

est_prob(40, 20, 3, 21)
## Proportion of sample means greater than 21: 0.015
